  "prompt": "Does a white background use more energy on a LCD than if it was set to black?",
  "response": "The energy consumption of an LCD display is generally consistent regardless of the color displayed on the screen. Unlike OLED displays, where each pixel is individually lit and darker colors can save energy, LCDs use a backlight that is always on when the screen is active. This means the energy consumption is primarily related to the brightness of the backlight rather than the colors shown on the screen. \n\nAs a result, whether you display a white or black background on an LCD, the difference in energy use is negligible, assuming the backlight brightness level remains the same. The primary way to reduce energy consumption on LCDs is by lowering the screen brightness or using energy-saving modes, rather than changing the display colors.",
